   "source": [
    "# ThemisAI Bias Detection Demo\n",
    "\n",
    "### Capsa automatically wraps ML workflows to achieve risk-aware learning and deployment.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "In this demo, we'll be demonstrating how **CAPSA**, the model-agnostic risk awareness framework that we've developed at Themis AI, can automatically detect bias in datasets of faces. Here, the dataset we've chosen here is the Celeb-A dataset, which containts over 200K celebrity images. We create a face classification task by choosing random samples from ImageNet as negatives."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First, we import the necessary dependencies, set some important hyperparameters, and load the data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import cv2\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import tensorflow as tf\n",
    "import time\n",
    "import h5py\n",
    "import sys\n",
    "import glob\n",
    "import functools\n",
    "from train_dataloader import TrainingDatasetLoader\n",
    "from tqdm import tqdm\n",
    "from helper import plot_k, plot_percentile, plot_frequencies"
   ]

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},

   "execution_count": 3,

    "batch_size = 32\n",
    "num_epochs = 6"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "data_path = tf.keras.utils.get_file(\n",

   "source": [
    "\"\"\"Function to define a standard CNN model\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "def make_standard_classifier(n_outputs=1, n_filters=12):\n",
    "  Conv2D = functools.partial(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D, padding='same', activation='relu')\n",
    "  BatchNormalization = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization\n",
    "  Flatten = tf.keras.layers.Flatten\n",
    "  Dense = functools.partial(tf.keras.layers.Dense, activation='relu')\n",
    "\n",
    "  model = tf.keras.Sequential([\n",
    "    Conv2D(filters=1*n_filters, kernel_size=5,  strides=2),\n",
    "    BatchNormalization(),\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Conv2D(filters=2*n_filters, kernel_size=5,  strides=2),\n",
    "    BatchNormalization(),\n",
    "\n",
    "    Conv2D(filters=4*n_filters, kernel_size=3,  strides=2),\n",
    "    BatchNormalization(),\n",
    "\n",
    "    Conv2D(filters=6*n_filters, kernel_size=3,  strides=2),\n",
    "    BatchNormalization(),\n",
    "\n",
    "    Flatten(),\n",
    "    Dense(512),\n",
    "    Dense(n_outputs, activation=None),\n",
    "  ])\n",
    "  model.build((None, 64, 64, 3))\n",
    "  return model\n",
    "\n",
    "standard_classifier = make_standard_classifier()"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Integrating Capsa to Create Risk-Aware AI Models\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, we import capsa, our risk-aware framework. We'll be showing two different ways of \"wrapping\" our models so that they are risk aware."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from capsa import wrap, VAEWrapper, HistogramCallback"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Method 1: The *wrap(...)* function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we wrap the standard classifier. In this example, we choose the VAE, or variational autoencoder, and analyze the biases in the dataset. The VAE can also be used to quantify epistemic uncertainty, which we will show here as well. With this one line, we've now created a risk-aware model!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "wrapping with: [<capsa.epistemic.VAE.VAEWrapper object at 0x7f962cd09b80>]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "wrapped_classifier = wrap(standard_classifier, aleatoric=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Method 2: Directly calling metric wrapper\n",
    "An alternate method of wrapping the model is using the Wrapper itself, and this is useful when we have more hyperparameters that we want to specify."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "wrapped_classifier = VAEWrapper(\n",
    "    standard_classifier,\n",
    "    latent_dim=latent_dim,\n",
    "    epistemic=True,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Capsa models are drop-in replacements for existing models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We choose hyperparameters, load our training data, and compile the model just as we would a normal Keras model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Training hyperparameters\n",
    "learning_rate = 1e-5\n",
    "\n",
    "wrapped_classifier.compile(\n",
    "    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate),\n",
    "    loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True),\n",
    "    metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.BinaryAccuracy()],\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Lastly, we fit the model. We can use any of the capabilities of a normal Keras model with the wrapped model, and fit is no exception."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "2404/2404 [==============================] - 48s 19ms/step - loss: 0.1000 - binary_accuracy: 0.9626 - val_loss: 0.0413 - val_binary_accuracy: 0.9862\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "if training:\n",
    "    history = wrapped_classifier.fit(\n",
    "        dataloader,\n",
    "        epochs=6,\n",
    "        batch_size=batch_size,\n",
    "        validation_data=test_dataloader,\n",
    "        callbacks=[HistogramCallback()]\n",
    "    )\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    history = wrapped_classifier.fit(\n",
    "        dataloader,\n",
    "        epochs=1,\n",
    "        batch_size=batch_size,\n",
    "        validation_data=test_dataloader,\n",
    "        callbacks=[HistogramCallback()]\n",
    "    )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if training:\n",
    "    wrapped_classifier.save_weights(\"wrapped_model_bias_and_epistemic_shuffled_0\")\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    path = \"/data/capsa/vae_face/\"\n",
    "    wrapped_classifier.load_weights(path + \"wrapped_model_bias_and_epistemic_shuffled_0\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Like before, we can call the Keras model again on a sample batch; this time, however, we get the output as well as the epistemic uncertainty per sample and the bias per sample"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of prediction outputs: 32\n",
      "Number of uncertainty outputs: 32\n",
      "Number of bias outputs: 32\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "prediction, uncertainty, bias = wrapped_classifier(sample_batch_imgs)\n",
    "print(f\"Number of prediction outputs: {len(prediction)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Number of uncertainty outputs: {len(uncertainty)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Number of bias outputs: {len(bias)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that our model is trained, we load the test dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We call the wrapped classifier on the test dataset and sort the dataset in order of increasing bias."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "predictions, uncertainty, bias = wrapped_classifier(test_img, softmax=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "bias = np.squeeze(bias)\n",
    "sorted_bias_inds = np.argsort(bias)\n",
    "sorted_biases = np.array(bias[sorted_bias_inds])\n",
    "sorted_images = np.array(test_img[sorted_bias_inds])\n",
    "sorted_labels = np.array(test_label[sorted_bias_inds])\n",
    "sorted_predictions = np.array(predictions)[sorted_bias_inds]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Shown below are the 20 images with the lowest bias (i.e. the least represented in the dataset). We can see that varied facial position and obstructing items such as hats and sunglasses are underrepresented in this dataset"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we see the top 20 samples that the dataset is biased towards. These are overwhemingly light-skinned females with light hair, and almost all the people in these images are directly facing the camera"

   "cell_type": "code",

    "plot_k(sorted_images[-20:])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we plot the average face by percentile. The top left image shows the average face of the bottom 5th percentile in terms of bias, and we can see that the average skin tone and hair color is darker than the faces in the higher percentiles. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "num_percentile_intervals = 10\n",
    "num_samples = len(test_img) // num_percentile_intervals\n",
    "all_imgs = []\n",
    "all_bias = []\n",
    "all_acc = []\n",
    "for percentile in range(num_percentile_intervals):\n",
    "    cur_imgs = sorted_images[percentile * num_samples : (percentile + 1) * num_samples]\n",
    "    cur_bias = sorted_biases[percentile * num_samples : (percentile + 1) * num_samples]\n",
    "    cur_labels = sorted_labels[percentile * num_samples : (percentile + 1) * num_samples]\n",
    "    cur_predictions = tf.nn.sigmoid(sorted_predictions[percentile * num_samples : (percentile + 1) * num_samples])\n",
    "    avged_imgs = tf.reduce_mean(cur_imgs, axis=0)\n",
    "    all_imgs.append(avged_imgs)\n",
    "    all_bias.append(tf.reduce_mean(cur_bias))\n",
    "    all_acc.append((cur_labels == np.rint(cur_predictions)).mean())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, we sort the data according to the biases and plot the average accuracy as a function of the percentile. We see here that the items with extremely low bias also have lower accuracy."

    "plt.title(\"Percentile vs. average accuracy\")\n",

   ]
